[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Understand Images https://page.gensparksite.com/v1/base64_upload/2595a9ace2ec8bb9d8b0e638dd182696 View Continue I’m going to quickly look up the exact model “Bell & Gossett reducing valve Part No. 110194, Model 6” so I can recommend a direct-replacement or a modern alternative with the right factory setpoint for a hydronic boiler (typically 12–15 psi). Then I’ll confirm specs (max pressure/temp, thread size, and whether it includes fast-fill) and share options like B&G 1156F or alternatives from Taco/Caleffi, along with settings and step-by-step replacement guidance. Using Tool | Parallel Search Bell & Gossett 110194 reducing valve model 6 set at 43 lbs Bell & Gossett model 6 reducing valve specs B&G reducing valve part 110194 Bell & Gossett 1156F factory setting 12 psi specs Taco boiler feed valve 3350 specs factory setting Caleffi 535H auto fill valve specs 12 psi View Quick assessment from your photos The brass can-shaped device is not a relief valve. It’s a Bell & Gossett pressure reducing valve (boiler feed valve), Model “#6,” Part No. 110194, factory set around 43–45 psi, 1/2\" NPT, max inlet 125 psi, max temp 225 F National Pump Supply Xylem/B&G submittal PDF URI. Your combo gauge shows about 15 psi and ~190 F when hot, which is in the typical operating range for many residential hydronic systems (cold fill usually 12–15 psi). Common boiler-fill regulators are factory set to 12 or 15 psi, not 43–45 psi Watts 1156F spec Taco 3350 spec. B&G explicitly notes their B-38/B-38TU are preset at 12 psi, while the No. 6 (yours) is preset around 45 psi—hence it’s the wrong model if the goal is maintaining a typical 12–15 psi boiler fill pressure Xylem/B&G instruction manual. Best replacement options to maintain stable boiler pressure (12–15 psi) Bell & Gossett B-38 or B-38TU (12 psi preset). Directly intended for boiler feed; B&G literature lists B-38/B-38TU preset at 12 psi for hydronic systems Xylem/B&G instruction manual. Watts 1156F/B1156F. Adjustable 10–25 psi, factory set at 15 psi; includes strainer; max pressure 100 psi; widely used and easy to set precisely Watts 1156F spec SupplyHouse listing. Taco 3350 series. Adjustable 10–50 psi, factory set at 12 psi; fast-fill button; max inlet 150 psi; purpose-built as a boiler feed PRV Taco spec sheet Boston Heating Supply. Why you shouldn’t re-use a #6 The #6 is a “high-pressure” reducing valve with an adjustment range 25–60 psi and factory set around 45 psi. That setting is above a typical residential boiler’s 30 psi safety relief rating, increasing the risk of nuisance relief lift or overpressure if the valve drifts or is misadjusted National Pump Supply Xylem/B&G submittal PDF. Recommended pick (simple, reliable) Go with a Watts 1156F (union style) set to 15 psi, or a Taco 3350 set to 12 psi. Both are proven, easy to adjust, and designed to maintain the correct boiler fill pressure range. Choose the one that matches your piping connection style (union vs NPT) and local availability Watts 1156F spec Taco spec sheet. Step-by-step SOP to replace and set the boiler feed valve Objective: Replace B&G #6 with a boiler-feed PRV that maintains 12–15 psi cold. Safety: Shut power to boiler. Allow system to cool below 100 F if possible. Close manual water supply before the PRV. Wear eye/hand protection. Step\tAction\tExpected input\tExpected output/result\tNotes/resources 1\tIdentify and tag valves\tLocate cold water shutoff before the PRV and isolation valves around the boiler\tValves closed, system isolated\tPrevents uncontrolled fill during swap 2\tRelieve pressure\tOpen a nearby drain/purge or a radiator bleeder\tSystem drops to ~0 psi\tWatch boiler gauge; capture/contain water 3\tRemove old B&G #6\tTwo wrenches to avoid twisting piping\tPRV removed from line\tThe #6 is 1/2\" NPT female in most installs National Pump Supply 4\tInstall backflow preventer if missing\tAdd a separate backflow preventer upstream (code in many areas)\tProper check/backflow installed\tMany combo “fill/backflow” assemblies exist; follow local code 5\tInstall new PRV (Watts 1156F or Taco 3350) with flow arrow correct\tTeflon tape/dope; union tailpiece if using union model\tLeak-free installation with serviceable union\tWatts 1156F factory 15 psi; Taco 3350 factory 12 psi Watts 1156F spec Taco spec 6\tPre-charge expansion tank to match cold fill\tIsolate tank; set air side to your target fill (12–15 psi)\tTank air charge equals setpoint\tMatching charge keeps pressure stable as the system heats 7\tSet PRV pressure\tUse screw: CW increases, CCW decreases; target 12–15 psi cold\tCold boiler gauge settles at setpoint\tWatts range 10–25 psi (factory 15). Taco range 10–50 (factory 12) Watts 1156F spec Taco spec 8\tFast-fill and purge air\tUse fast-fill lever/button if equipped while purging\tAir expelled; system fills quickly\tTaco has fast-fill button; many 1156F variants include fast-fill features Taco spec 9\tHeat up and verify\tRestore power; run to operating temp\tHot pressure typically 18–25 psi; no relief lift\tAdjust PRV and verify expansion tank if pressure rises too high 10\tLeak check and document\tInspect all joints; tag setpoint\tDry joints; documented set pressure\tLeave a service note with model and final setting Decision guide: which valve to buy Keep it B&G? Choose B-38/B-38TU preset 12 psi—designed for boiler feed. Do not re-install a #6 unless your system truly requires 25–60 psi, which would be unusual for small residential hydronics Xylem/B&G instruction manual. Want quick availability and easy setting? Watts 1156F is nearly universal; set to 15 psi and you’re done Watts 1156F spec. Prefer a 12 psi factory preset and a fast-fill button? Taco 3350 is a strong pick Taco spec Global Industrial. What to set it to For most 1–2 story homes, set the cold fill to 12–15 psi using the PRV adjustment. These devices come from the factory in that range (Watts 15 psi, Taco 12 psi), which is why they’re ideal for maintaining stable pressure in residential hydronic systems Watts 1156F spec Taco 3350 spec. Bottom line Replace the B&G #6 (high-pressure) with a true boiler feed regulator: B&G B-38/B-38TU (12 psi), Watts 1156F (15 psi), or Taco 3350 (12 psi). Any of these will maintain the correct pressure and reduce nuisance relief-valve lifting and system stress when installed and set properly Xylem/B&G instruction manual Watts 1156F spec Taco 3350 spec. Want me to spec an exact SKU that matches your piping (union vs NPT, sweat, integral backflow) and create a shopping list? If you share your connection type and whether you already have a separate backflow preventer, I’ll finalize the parts and settings. Upgrade Your Boiler's Pressure Reducing Valve: Fix High Pressure and Optimize Performance Upgrade Your Boiler's Pressure Reducing Valve: Fix High Pressure and Optimize Performance This article guides homeowners through identifying an incorrectly installed Bell & Gossett Model #6 pressure reducing valve (PRV) on a hydronic heating system, which is factory-set too high for typical residential boilers. It explains why a high-pressure PRV can lead to issues and provides recommended replacement options like the Watts 1156F or Taco 3350 series, designed to maintain the optimal 12-15 psi cold fill pressure. A step-by-step standard operating procedure for safe replacement and proper setting of the new boiler feed valve is included, ensuring stable system pressure and preventing nuisance relief valve lifts. See more I have a four story brownstone, and often the top floor is much colder than the lower level.So we have a higher pressure reducing setting.So that the top floor is able to have the correct heat setting without it being too cold.That's why we have overcompensated, because in the building, we were experiencing something different now.Can you still recommend what the best option is?I do not want to have the lower level.Very hot and the top floor very cold.Because the heat is not properly circular To tailor a safe fix for a four‑story brownstone, I’ll pull authoritative references for: 1) required static fill pressure vs. building height, 2) typical 30 psi relief limits, 3) expansion tank precharge rules, and 4) boiler-feed PRV adjustment ranges. Then I’ll give you a step-by-step SOP with calculations, recommended valve models, pump/balancing tactics, and verification steps. Using Tool | Parallel Search hydronic boiler static fill pressure formula 0.433 height feet top radiator expansion tank precharge equal to system fill pressure hydronic typical boiler safety relief valve 30 psi residential hydronic hydronic circulator sizing differential pressure vs flow top floor cold zone balancing valves hydronic uneven heat Bell & Gossett B-38 preset 12 psi manual View You’re right to focus on pressure, but the fix isn’t “more pressure everywhere.” It’s the right cold fill pressure for a 4‑story building, plus proper expansion-tank setup and hydraulic balancing so the pump actually moves hot water to the top without cooking the lower floors. What you have now and why it’s fighting you The brass can-shaped device in your photo is a Bell & Gossett “#6” pressure reducing valve (PRV), part 110194, factory set around 43–45 psi with an adjustable range of roughly 25–60 psi. That is a high‑pressure boiler feed valve, not the low‑pressure type used on most hydronic systems. Max ratings 125 psi, 225 F National Pump Supply Xylem/B&G submittal PDF B&G manual noting #6 preset vs low‑pressure B‑38. Your combo gauge shows roughly 15 psi while hot and ~190 F, which is on the low side for a 4‑story building; that helps explain why the top floor lags. Static head matters: you must maintain a few psi of positive pressure at the highest radiator when the water is cold or air won’t purge and flow will be weak upstairs JMP blog CHC Hydro. What pressure do you actually need for a 4‑story brownstone? The cold fill pressure should equal the vertical height (in feet) from the boiler gauge to the highest emitter divided by 2.31, then add 3–5 psi safety margin to ensure positive pressure at the top: Pfill ≈ Height/2.31 + 3–5 psi. Equivalently, 0.433 psi per foot + 3–5 psi JMP blog CHC Hydro. Example: If the top radiator is ~40 ft above the boiler gauge, Pfill ≈ (40/2.31) + 3–5 ≈ 17.3 + 3–5 = 20–22 psi cold. That’s enough to purge air and feed the top story without pushing the system toward the 30 psi relief valve limit as it heats up PexUniverse overview Watts 174A spec, 30 psi typical. Critical companion step: expansion tank setup The diaphragm expansion tank’s air precharge must match the chosen cold fill pressure (or be within a pound). If the tank is still at 12 psi while you try to run a 20–22 psi system, pressure will spike when hot, forcing the relief to dribble and masking true circulator issues. Set the tank precharge to the same cold fill pressure with the system at zero water pressure before refilling EngProGuides Calefactio. Recommendation: the right PRV plus balance plan Replace the B&G #6 with a boiler‑feed PRV that can be set precisely to the calculated cold fill (likely ~20–22 psi for a 4‑story). Good choices: Watts 1156F/B1156F: adjustable 10–25 psi, factory set 15 psi; integrate a strainer; rated 100 psi/212 F. Set it to your calculated fill pressure Watts 1156F data sheet. Taco 3350 series: adjustable 10–50 psi, factory set 12 psi; fast‑fill button; max inlet 150 psi/210 F. Also easy to set to 20–22 psi Taco spec. Why not keep the B&G #6? Its adjustment range starts around 25 psi. That forces you too close to the 30 psi safety cap and can cause nuisance relief discharge—especially as the water expands on heat-up National Pump Supply PexUniverse. Hydraulic fixes so the top floor warms without roasting the lower floors Balance the flows: Install or adjust manual balancing valves or thermostatic radiator valves (TRVs). Balancing adds resistance to “short” circuits on the lower stories so adequate flow reaches the top. This is the standard cure for uneven distribution in multi‑branch systems TSI, hydronic system balancing Ebara balancing primer Armstrong balancing theory. Circulator strategy: If you have zone valves or big flow swings, consider an ECM “smart” circulator set to constant pressure mode. That holds differential pressure steady as valves open/close, ensuring the top floor still gets flow while the lower floors don’t hog it Xylem on speed control Taco pump curves primer Caleffi hydronic fundamentals. Air elimination: After setting the proper cold fill, purge the risers and radiators on the top floor. Positive pressure at the high point is what lets automatic vents and manual bleeders actually clear air; under‑pressurized systems trap air and starve upper loops JMP blog. Action plan (tactical SOP) Goal: Even heat on all 4 floors with safe pressure margins; hot pressure stays <25 psi, no relief lift at 30 psi; top-floor radiators fully hot. Measure building static height Input: Tape or laser measurement from the boiler’s pressure gauge centerline to the highest radiator/top of system. Method: Record total vertical feet; if unknown, estimate floor-to-floor height and sum. Output: Height in feet used for fill-pressure calculation. Example: 40 ft. Calculate the correct cold fill pressure Input: Height (ft). Method: Pfill = Height/2.31 + 3–5 psi margin (or Height×0.433 + 3–5). Output: Target Pfill (likely 20–22 psi for ~40 ft) JMP blog CHC Hydro. Replace PRV with an adjustable boiler feed regulator Input: Choose one: Watts 1156F (union or NPT to match your piping; 10–25 psi range) Watts 1156F data sheet. Taco 3350 (10–50 psi range; fast‑fill button) Taco spec. Method: Isolate water, drop system to zero psi, swap valve, ensure a separate backflow preventer upstream if local code requires. Output: New PRV installed, adjustable to exact Pfill. Set the expansion tank precharge Input: Target Pfill from step 2. Method: With system at zero water pressure and tank isolated/drained, set tank air to target Pfill. Reopen isolation valve. Output: Tank precharge equals cold fill—stabilizes hot pressure rise and prevents relief lifting EngProGuides Calefactio. Adjust PRV and fill/purge Input: Target Pfill; a hose at purge valves on high risers; fast‑fill feature if present. Method: Set PRV to Pfill; fast‑fill while purging top floors until air-free; lock adjustment. Output: Cold system pressure at target (e.g., 21 psi); all risers/emitters bled. Verify operating pressure versus the 30 psi safety limit Input: Boiler gauge when hot during a long run. Method: Observe hot pressure; aim for 18–25 psi. If it pushes >25, the tank may be undersized or undercharged; correct before proceeding. Output: Hot pressure stable <25 psi; safety relief (30 psi) stays closed PexUniverse Watts 174A product spec. Balance distribution Input: Manual balancing valves and/or TRVs on lower floors. Method: Slightly throttle lower-floor circuits until the top floor achieves the same return temperature rise and room temps track setpoints; leave upstairs wide open. If you have zone valves, confirm each zone reaches design flow; add a differential bypass or use an ECM constant-pressure circulator if zones “steal” flow when others close. Output: Even heat across floors; delta‑T and room temps converge; pump doesn’t surge/whine; fewer short‑cycles TSI balancing Ebara balancing primer Xylem on speed control. Circulator check (upgrade if needed) Input: Current circulator model and curve; total system head estimate; measured supply/return temps. Method: Compare pump curve to system demand; if undersized head is starving the top floor, replace with an ECM circulator sized for required head/flow and run in constant pressure mode to maintain upstairs flow without overheating downstairs. Output: Stable top-floor heat, quieter system, lower electricity use Taco pump curves Caleffi hydronic fundamentals. What to buy now (practical picks) Pressure reducing valve: Watts 1156F (10–25 psi) if you want fine control right in the needed range; or Taco 3350 (10–50 psi) if you like the fast‑fill button and broader range. Either one will let you set 20–22 psi precisely for a 4‑story. Your current B&G #6 starts too high (25+ psi) and isn’t ideal here Watts 1156F Taco 3350 B&G #6 details. Expansion tank: Verify model and size; if your hot pressure still climbs near 30 psi after the precharge fix, you likely need the next tank size up (the cure for hot pressure creep) EngProGuides. Balancing/TRVs: Add manual balance valves on lower floors or TRVs on radiators to self‑throttle overheated rooms; the result is even temperatures and better comfort without cranking whole‑building pressure TSI. Answering your concern directly Yes, we can keep the lower level from running hot while the top stays cold—without cranking the whole system’s pressure into the danger zone. The combination of: Correct cold fill (likely ~20–22 psi), Matching expansion-tank precharge, Proper balancing/ECM circulator control, will give the top-floor its share of flow and deliver even heat across all four stories within the 30 psi safety envelope JMP blog PexUniverse Xylem speed control. If you can share: The vertical height from boiler gauge to the highest radiator, Your circulator model number, Whether you have zone valves or TRVs today, I’ll calculate your exact cold fill target, confirm the right PRV setting, and give you a precise balancing and pump setting recipe for your building. Hydronic System Balancing: Achieving Even Heat in Multi-Story Buildings Hydronic System Balancing: Achieving Even Heat in Multi-Story Buildings This guide addresses uneven heating in multi-story hydronic systems, emphasizing the critical role of correct cold fill pressure calculation, proper expansion tank precharge, and selecting the right pressure reducing valve. It outlines an action plan for hydraulic balancing using control valves and optimizing circulator performance to ensure consistent heat distribution across all floors within safe operating pressures. See more Make a detailed table of all the supplies needed and live links for the how to purchase them I’m going to pull current product pages for all recommended components (PRV options, backflow preventer, expansion tank, balancing valves, circulators, air eliminator/vents, isolation/purge valves, gauges, and install consumables) so I can give you a shopping-ready table with live purchase links and accurate specs. Then I’ll format the supplies into a step-by-step bill of materials aligned to the SOP. Using Tool | Parallel Search Watts 9D backflow preventer hydronic fill purchase Caleffi QuickSetter 132 balancing valve purchase Danfoss RA2000 thermostatic radiator valve purchase Grundfos Alpha2 constant pressure circulator purchase Taco 0018e constant pressure ECM circulator purchase Spirovent air eliminator purchase View Using Tool | Parallel Search Taco 4900 air separator purchase Amtrol Extrol #30 expansion tank specs purchase Webstone isolation flange purge valve circulator purchase Watts 1156F union purchase link Taco 3350 PRV purchase link Caleffi 5020 automatic air vent purchase View Using Tool | Parallel Search 0-60 psi pressure gauge 1/4 NPT boiler hydronic purchase RectorSeal Tru-Blu pipe thread sealant purchase PTFE thread seal tape purchase 1/2 inch Boiler drain valve 3/4\" garden hose purchase Radiator bleed key purchase Fernco hose for hydronic purge 5/8 in purchase View Below is your shopping‑ready Bill of Materials for fixing heat imbalance in a 4‑story brownstone, with live purchase links and “expected input/output” so you (or your contractor) know exactly what to set, measure, or decide for each item. Assumptions behind these picks Target cold fill pressure: typically 20–22 psi for a ~40 ft rise from boiler to top radiator (Height/2.31 + 3–5 psi), so you maintain positive pressure at the top without approaching the 30 psi safety limit when hot JMP CHC Hydro. Most residential boiler relief valves are 30 psi, so we keep hot pressure under ~25 psi after the expansion tank is set correctly Watts 174A PexUniverse explainer. Bill of Materials (with links) Component (click to view)\tPurpose / When to use\tModel / Spec\tKey ratings / Adjustments\tWhere to buy (live link)\tExpected input from you\tExpected output after install\tQty (est.)\tNotes / Rationale Pressure Reducing Valve (PRV) – Option A: Watts 1156F\tMaintain correct cold fill (set to your calculated 20–22 psi)\t1156F, union or NPT variants\tAdjustable 10–25 psi; factory 15 psi; max 100 psi; 212 F; integral strainer Watts datasheet\tFerguson listing or Watts 1156F page\tMeasure building height; compute target cold fill (likely 20–22 psi); choose connection (union/NPT)\tStable cold fill pressure; easier purging; top floor heats reliably\t1\tEasy fine‑tuning in the 10–25 psi range makes it ideal for multi‑story buildings Watts datasheet Pressure Reducing Valve – Option B: Taco 3350\tSame role; adds fast‑fill button\t3350 (T3 threaded or press/union variants)\tAdjustable 10–50 psi; factory 12 psi; max inlet 150 psi; 210 F; fast‑fill Taco spec\tHome Depot 3350‑T3 or Global Industrial\tSame as above; decide if you want a fast‑fill button\tQuick purging with fast‑fill; precise set to 20–22 psi\t1\tBroader range if your measured static head needs >25 psi Taco spec Combo backflow + feed assembly\tCode-friendly makeup water; simplifies install\tWatts B911S‑M3 (9D + 1156F combo)\tIntegrated backflow preventer + feed regulator; high‑capacity fill Watts 911 page\tAmazon listing B911S‑M3\tConfirm local code; select sweat vs threaded\tOne compact unit: prevents backflow and holds set pressure\t1\tCleanest single‑body solution for serviceability Watts 911 page Backflow preventer (if using standalone PRV)\tRequired in many jurisdictions\tWatts 9D dual‑check with atmospheric vent\tHydronic feed line backflow protection Watts 9D\tWatts 9D page\tChoose size/ends to match PRV\tCode compliance; protects potable water\t1\tPair with Watts 1156F if not u